Based on the foregoing observations, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the following:
• The Inventory Committee headed by the General Services Officer prepare the inventory list and perform the actual and complete inventory taking of all the municipal properties, prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and submit to the Municipal Accountant and Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; 
• The General Services Officer prepare and maintain the required Property Cards and update the Property Cards record and update the ARE to facilitate the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with the accounting records;
• The Accounting Department exhaust all efforts to fully identify the PPEs included in the beginning/unidentified balances. Secure the necessary documents to support those PPEs to be able to reconcile with the Inventory Report of GSO. Also, trace those PPEs without depreciation and with negative balances to establish their correct carrying value. Likewise, review the composition of the accounts under those PPEs and identify the appropriate classification for those items identified in the audit. Secure proper documentation before effecting the necessary adjusting entries for erroneous recording or for inclusion to ensure that the amounts are valid and conform to the rules and regulations that will cover such adjustments; and
• The Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, to facilitate the reconciliation of both records.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
• Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC), the Bid and Award Committee (BAC) and the Municipal Engineer to ensure the timely, effective and efficient implementation of the approved priority development projects within their targeted completion period;
• Municipal Budget Officer to record obligations based on the actual contract amount and to coordinate with the MPDC for the implemented projects under 20 per cent DF to ensure that these are duly obligated;
• Municipal Development Council to conduct in-depth planning for prioritization of PPAs in the 20 per cent Development Fund by the consensus of the constituents and coordination with the MPDC to avoid realignment and sudden change of projects intended for current year’s implementation; and
• Municipal Budget Officer and MPDC to prepare Supplemental Annual Investment Plan/Procurement Plan for all procurement of goods/infrastructures projects under Supplemental Budgets and realignment of fund.

