We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
Inventory and Appraisal Committee  to conduct complete inventory taking of all the municipal properties, prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and submit to the Municipal Accountant and Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of every year;
The General Services Officer, after the preparation of said RPCPPE, reconcile with that of the Accounting records and  exert  effort for the  disposal of  all unserviceable properties;  obtain  documents of the donated  vehicles from PCSO/donor agency, for immediate recording by the  Municipal Accountant in the PPE accounts;
The Municipal Accountant and the designated GSO maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, to facilitate the reconciliation of both records; and
Cause the titling of the parcels of land in favor of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
Municipal Assessor to copy furnish the Municipal Treasurer of its monthly assessment report;
Municipal Treasurer see to it that their database tallied with the assessment roll of the Municipal Assessor to ensure the accuracy of computed 1% basic real property tax and 1% for SEF; and
Municipal Accountant ensure that only the collectibles for the current year are set-up at the beginning of the year and it should be backed-up with a certified list of taxpayers;
Likewise, the Municipal Treasurer provide the Municipal Accountant with a complete list of delinquent taxpayers as of December 31, 2016. Thereafter, the Municipal Accountant make the necessary adjusting entries to recognize the correct Real Property Tax Receivables and Special Education Tax Receivables in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor together with the management:
Create a team compose of department heads to make a formal study in improving the revenue of the market  and immediately act upon the various causes of losses;
Accept new lessees for the unoccupied/vacant stalls in the market;
Institute actions for the intensive collection of delinquency/arrearages pertaining to stall rights and  monthly rental of stall fees and impose the sanctions against erring stallholders;
Require the Supervising Administrative Officer (Market  Officer–In-Charge)  to maintain a ledger card and control list of uncollected payments for stall rights and daily rentals on a monthly basis;
Enjoin the Business Permit and Licensing Office (Office of the MPDC) and Municipal Treasurer’s Office in monitoring and exacting permit fee and other regulatory fees for businesses not only in the market but in all business establishments under its jurisdiction;
Make a feasibility study for the operation of the Municipality’s own slaughterhouse in order to ensure safety and quality of meat products being sold in the market; and
Make a study also for other possible use of the slaughterhouse located in the lot of the Municipality’s dumpsite to avoid disallowance in audit.

We recommended that the Honorable Mayor enjoin the Municipal Engineer to:
Prepare the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) in accordance with the DPWH Department Order No. 22, Series of 2015;
Charge the contractors with liquidated damages in the amount of ₱101,916.67;
Display tarpaulin signboards at project location to inform the public; and
See to it that the projects were done in accordance with the approved program of works.
